10 cm X 10 cm, 18 mg/cm**2 natural carbon target.
The analysis of data consisted of  initially  sorting
the  proton data that arrived into excitation energy
spectra.  Relative yields and angular  distributions
were  obtained  for  four  peaks observed in spectra
with the energies E-exc = 0.00, 2.12,  5.02, and 6.8
MeV.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.267, p.51 (1976)

x4freetext: Statistical errors.
Systematic  errors  were  estimated  as to
be about of 20%.
The corrections   were  made  for  variation  in  the
tagging efficiency with photon energy,  for  changes
in the counting rates,  and for inelastic scattering
of protons within the Ge(Li)-detector.
Cross section measurements for the reaction C-12(g,p)
leading to resolved,  low-lying,  excited states  of
B-11  are presented.  The measurements were obtained
using tagged photons of 49 - 78.5 MeV and  for  mean
laboratory  proton  emission  angles  from 65 to 115
degrees.  The proton excitation energy  spectra  are
dominated   by   the   ground   state  (3/2-),  2.13
MeV(1/2-),  5.02  MeV(3/2-),  and  6.8  MeV  doublet
(7/2-,1/2+) states of B-11. No evidence is found for
population of known 4.45 MeV (5/2-) state.
